The adult gallery contains two egg galleries that branch from the central nuptial chamber. One egg gallery extends from the nuptial chamber perpendicular to the grain of wood and the second gallery extends at a 45° angle to the grain (Fig. 24). Galleries are frequently initiated near branch crotches and disguised under rough patches of bark. The adult gallery deeply scores the sapwood and lightly scores the cambium. The adult galleries range in size from 1.9-6.5 cm in length. Eggs are laid in niches on both sides of each egg gallery and larval mines radiate perpendicular to the egg gallery forming a fan shaped pattern. The larval mines gradually diverge and lightly etch the sapwood. Pupation occurs in the sapwood (
Edson 1967
).
